segments.text: This is a Tape 2 interview with Chuy Hinojosa on July 29, 1987.
We were talking about the sequence of department heads, which is becoming difficult to keep straight.
Anyway, Gordon Echols was asked to become interim department head in the fall of 1987.

Gordon continued in that capacity until the 15th of December when after he lost his wife he became incapable of carrying on as department head and was relieved by the department faculty decided that it had to have a more active department head
who was capable of carrying on the necessary tasks that come the way of the department.
And so Don Sweeney, as acting dean, appointed Wolf Roessler as interim department head, which
position he maintains today.
The original degree, we offer, of course, a master's of urban planning.
And then since then, the doctor of environmental design has been changed into a PhD.
We had the doctor of environmental design.
Then the MSLD, the Master of Science in Land Development, was instituted when?
That was in 1985.
I believe so.
It's one year.
full-year 36 credit hour program.
36 credit hour.
Right.
With one summer lab.
Yes, a whole summer lab.
What course is that?
Plan 667.
That's when they apply all they have studied in the fall and spring, the theory, you know, they apply it in a laboratory for the whole summer.
Usually dealing with large-scale land development companies.
city projects.
What do you view as the future for the department?
Well, that's a hard question to answer.
I think that the department has been answering the needs of the field in terms of producing people in urban planning that are qualified for the field.
I see more
more cities now hiring planners for their own staffs.
As the federal government has cut back on a lot of the funding that before would provide federal assistance to communities for planning, I see now communities taking that on themselves.
And the interesting thing is that they're coming to that conclusion themselves, where they want to have planning studies done for their communities.
And at least when they're able to, they hire their own planners afterwards.
Many of our interns who have served in communities for at least three months, four months, or half a year have consistently been hired as permanent staff people in planning departments.
So I see that as a healthy trend that I would hope will continue to generate a demand for planning.
There seems to be in Texas more of a recognition of the need for planning, something that we haven't had in the state.
Contrast, say, to California or Florida, which have much longer experiences with planning.
In fact, they have mandated planning.
As well as Oregon.
In Oregon, exactly.
And I think maybe Massachusetts.
There are a few states that have this, but we don't have that in Texas.
We have been a pioneer in that regard here in the state as a school in establishing a career in a field that is not as well established and as well understood.
So I think as the state grows and they see the need for learning what other states have done, there seems to be an awareness of the need for the field of planning to be established.
And I think we stand a good chance of providing that support.
Thank you very much for your time and to have an accurate
chronology of your various planning assignments and your continuing involvement in planning education.
Thank you, Bob.

Yeah, well, one of the things that we forgot to discuss earlier, and some of the contributions that have been made by the Department to the State of Texas and the country, and not only in higher education, but in public education,
It's a short course that you helped establish in Texas, remember?
The Commissioner's short course.
And I think you had a hand in that with your experience from California.
And suggesting that something like that would be very valuable here, too.
And it was embraced, and people ran with it.
And it's been now, I don't know how many years now, 14 years or something it's been offered?
Since 1971.
1971, so that would make it...
16 years.
It wasn't too far off.
And that's been a good effort.
It came out of this department and so the faculty member taking that initiative.
And I think you have also expressed an interest in working with local public schools.
I believe, did you get a grant or something to

Pilot maybe a little program with one of the local schools to work with young kids and showing them what the field of planning is about and what it deals with so they can begin to develop an understanding.
And I think you're right.
I agree that we need to, as a field, communicate more with the general public in this area so they understand that the field can offer them something.
For example, when I tell people that I'm a city planner, they say, well, what's that?
they just are mystified by it.
Well, if you think about it, it's a relatively new field.
It really became formalized, although it's very old in many ways, too.

It became formalized in 1935, I think it was the first course that was offered at Harvard, and then in Pennsylvania they were immediately thereafter in 1936, with the first attempts at formal curriculums.
I think there's a lot of work to be done in terms of what professional planners do to make themselves known to the
American public.
Very much so.
I agree with you.
In fact, I made similar suggestions on the board of APA that we should communicate more with the general public and less with ourselves.
We do a lot of talking amongst ourselves, but not enough with you.
Yes, you're right.
I think that's an important area that has to be worked on.
Yeah.
End of interview.
This is August 3rd, 1987.
This is Bob Cornish.
We're in my office, and I'm interviewing Jim Gardner.
Jim,
First of all, go over your education in planning, where you went to school, and any comments you want to make about that.
Well, I think getting into the planning education program was an outgrowth of my being in an architectural program at USC, University of Southern California.

and being exposed to a person who stimulated me, as well as a lot of others, Cy Eisner, Simon Eisner, who, as you know, is the, along with Gallion, who happened to be the dean at the time of the school of architecture, wrote The Urban Pattern, and took one class from him, one of those
overview classes that all architects were supposed to take.
And it got me thinking about going into graduate school.
And I checked on them, Cal, USC, Berkeley.
I looked into some of the other programs, including MIT.
And I qualified.
I don't know why.
the normal MIT type would be, I don't think.

But the program was pretty non-technically oriented, due to the nature of the main faculty, Adams, Howard, and Greeley, who were a firm, incidentally, as you know, a consulting firm, and had quite a wide practice in the wing.
That was Jack Howard?
Yeah.
What year was that?
1952, I believe.
Yellow pipe.
I could look it up, but I don't know.
All right.
Whatever.
And spent two years in graduate school, which was a good experience for me, you know, personally.
Just being in New England with my wife.
And came back to California, where I had been the better part of my youth.
And got a position in San Bernardino as the third man on a three-man staff.

and for the city yes Dick Garrett was my immediate superior very a good person and a good planner I think I disagree with some of the directions that the program is going but that had nothing to do with the fact that I was lucky to get a opportunity to go to Stockton a year after I'd been in
in San Bernardino, and became a member of the staff under Stan Ott.
When he resigned, I was selected as the planning director.
What year was that?
That would have been about 55, 54, 55.
I was in Mill Valley at that time.
Yeah, right.
I occasionally ran into you in the AIP meetings.
Yeah.
Yeah, the Northern California section.
And I stayed in Stockton for about 10 years, I guess.
10 years as planning director.
That's quite a long time.
Yeah, it was.
Went through one of the early urban renewal programs that
We worked with, I'll drop another name.
I can't think of it right now.
John Hurt.
John Hurt.
H-I-R-T-O-N. E-N. E-N.
He was one of the early bright young boys in urban renewal.
Was he with the Chamber of Commerce originally in Stockton?
No, I don't believe so.
He was selected by the, I was interim head of the urban renewal program.
They didn't have a formal director for about a year.
So as planning director, I sort of took over that duty also.
We went to, I went to a conference, a narrow conference, I believe it was in St. Louis or someplace.
And we heard about this young boy, young man who... N-A-H-R-O.
Right.
A young fellow who had been working with one of the well-known programs in Little Rock, Arkansas.
I can't think of the director.
At that time, he was a biggie.
And so we were lucky, I thought, and it turned out he did a good job in Stockton, John, and
went on to become UMTA and all those things in Washington and subsequently Spur in San Francisco and that.
But get back to my historical background in planning.
I left Stockton when an opportunity came up for a chance to work for

a large quote-unquote engineering planning firm, Wilsingham and Blair, which later became Wilsingham, and spent two years there and became acquainted with such notable planners as Jesus Hinojosa, Robert Cornish, Joseph McGraw, and others.
few others who didn't make it to A&M.
It was sort of a breeding ground for, as it turned out, a sizable portion of the planning faculty later on at Texas A&M.
And it really comprised the original faculty entirely.
True.
I was probably the first full-time faculty, if you exclude the fact that Joe McGraw was here first as the only

paid help after having started the program with the help of then-President General Rutter and most effectively, Edward Romanek, who Joseph McGraw had worked with and gone to school with, I believe, earlier.
I think in Oklahoma.
Yeah.
And interestingly enough, Joe, in his previous experience at A&M,
taught to undergrad Jesus or Chewie in architecture.
So we all had sort of an architectural background.
In fact, we all did.
All sort of us.
Yeah, right.
Which you would think had given the program a pretty sharp, definite, physical direction.
But because of the nature of it,
the four that I mentioned, which were basically the faculty for the first 10 years, we didn't overemphasize that.
I don't think consciously, but it just, particularly when I joined the faculty in 66, Joe had started the program with six students, one of which was a
former neighbor in San Bruno, California, that he solicited to come.
Who was that?
Mike Harney.
Mike Harney?
You remember him, don't you?
And incidentally, among the six first students were one of the few blacks that's gone through the program.
I was thinking the other day that since there were six students, we had
Some 16 percent of the student body were minority blacks.
It was just higher than the history of the program or the history of A&M.
Is Mike black?
No.
This was Wendell Smith.
Oh, Wendell, yeah.
Whose father was dean at Prairie View at the time.
Yeah, of engineering.
Yeah.
Well, was he in the first class?
Either the first or second, very close to it.
Well, you know, Wendell was responsible for me being at A&M.
No, I didn't know that.
Oh, yes.
Should I tell you how that happened?
I think that's pertinent to the paper.
Sure.
Joe McGraw, when Wendell graduated, he told Wendell to get out of Texas, that he had no future in Texas.
He should go to California.
And when he got to California, he suggested that he look up some of Joe's old friends, and I was one of them.
So Wendell called me on the telephone and invited me to dinner.
And they were living in Menlo Park, East Menlo Park, which, of course, is all black.
And also there at that same meeting was Cliff Graves and his wife.
And Cliff had just returned from Washington, DC, where he had been looking for housing.
as he had been appointed an assistant to the director of Bureau of Management and Budget in the Nixon administration.
So there were four blacks and one white at Denrick.
And it was the first time I had been a minority.

And it was really quite funny because they had gone around the table and everybody was talking about what they'd been doing lately and Cliff had and his wife, both very elegant people by the way, and Cliff is currently the county administrator for San Diego County.
Cliff was enumerating the various amusing circumstances that they
face when they got to Washington looking for housing as blacks.
Because with his salary level, they could afford almost anything.
And the very trumped-up stories they'd get when they looked at high-quality housing.
And then it came my turn to say what I'd been doing lately.
And I announced that I had resigned from ABAC the week before.
And Wendell very seriously said, Bob, what
is the region ever going to do without you?
At which I laughed hysterically and said, the region will never even know I'm gone.
But I had hoped to study landscape architecture privately and race my sailboat seriously and do some gardening and drop out for a couple of years, which at the time I could afford to do.
And so apparently Wendell called Joe at Texas A&M and said, hey, this guy's on the loose.
You better get a calling to him.
And so that's what happened.
So it's because we're black that I'm here at A&M.
And I've talked with Wendell several times subsequently, and they're doing very well.
And he's turned out to be an excellent planner.
He's working for us.
HEW in the San Francisco office now.
He went to Union City first, I think.
Yeah.
As a planner.
Yeah.

And was there about a year, and the planning director left, and they pushed him into the role of acting planning director, and I told him not to take it unless they gave him the salary and the title to go with the responsibility.
And he then forced their hand, and he did become the planning director.
which was quite something to be a black and a planning director, even in California in those days.
But then he left and went to HUD in the San Francisco regional office, and did some good work for HUD, and then went on to HEW in terms of civil rights and that sort of thing.
You're still in San Francisco?
Still, and they're living in Fremont, as far as I know.
We had some interesting people back in those days, to say the least.
In fact, I was thinking the other day about the difference in the kinds of students from the early, say, 20 years ago.
And today, although I haven't been in the last two or three years that close to the students,
I have taught a class, and I have a rough idea of what some of them are like, today's students are like.
In some respects, it's a little disappointing, because I think most of us, what I mean, the early faculty, let's call them the four horsemen, were fairly activist-oriented.
not, what's the word I'm thinking of, the old advocacy types necessarily, because all planning was advocacy, and you're not a planner unless you're advocating something.
But anyway, we were all fairly active, and our students, I think, made us that way, even if we didn't want to be in it,
They were oriented toward what was going on in the world.
And this was the late 60s that I started.
So there was still that feeling from the, that characterized the 60s now.
The era of social unrest.
Right.
And consciousness, social consciousness among the students was much more evident than it is, I think, today.
And that's not necessarily bad.
That's a reflection of the country, obviously, and the nature of society generally today.
But I think we missed a little something.
For instance, we are missing it now.
We had the two cities had a group, maybe you remember it, called Twin City
I'm thinking it's mission because there is such a thing, but it was a Twin City organization.
I don't know what, that's not important.
But it was a spinoff or an outgrowth of the Martin Luther King assassination, and I can't think of when that was, but it was a little later on in the period, where this informal group of
not necessarily all black, but just all people who were interested in bettering social conditions, got together on a local level, two cities.
Of course, Bryan has, as had then as it has now, a predominance of black people.
And the college station had, obviously, the students.
And the two got along pretty well, the two groups.
They did some interesting things.

That was also the time where I believe where some of our students along with the primary stimulus I think was architecture students got this house loaned to them over there in the east side of town and put some sweat into it and build a thing.
It never really came off.
It was called Cisco.
Right.
It had good intentions.
They were doing it in other parts of the country.
Yeah, community design centers.
Yeah, design centers.
It never came off as well as it might have.
But to me, an example of what isn't happening today.
You know, I took a group of architecture students back to Howard University.
And when I was here, my first year in the Department of Architecture, I became the faculty lead on the Cisco project.
Oh, you did?
Yeah.
I went back to Howard with them for a conference of all the people from around the country that were involved with community design centers.
And that provided some real stimulus to the program here.
And that continued for another couple of years, and then it just sort of fell by the wayside.
I'm not sure where in the sequence.
I was, again, thinking of how the outreach type thing manifested itself in two other things.
One was, that I can recall, one was a proposal to locate a high school and college station.
which had a lot of planning implications, we thought.
And so the faculty, I think maybe they were just Joe and I at that time, took a pretty strong position and we went to the meetings and had great arguments with the people on the other side.
And the students did too.
They made up brochures and handed them out and flyers and handed them out.
And we had a great rapport with the faculty and students on an issue outside of the classroom.
Another one was an effort by, of course, that issue was finally decided by Bill Finch.
Yeah.

We simply gave the site to the city, or the school board, in effect, and claimed that the other site, which we thought was better, couldn't be obtained because it was a little old lady who Pappy said,
Daddy said, always stay with the land that you live in.
You don't have any problems at all.
Anyway, another one was even more interesting, I think, because it got really into some serious politics, namely university.
When the university wanted to set up an airport authority, and Joe at that time, Joe McGraw had been
had run for council and been elected.
I think the first time he ran, he was not elected.
And he was elected and called for, because they were going to tie in the two cities and the county, but not give them the proper authority.
The university was still going to run the show, but the tax base was going to be from the cities.
Anyway, it's too complicated to get into here.
But subsequently, he got it to he and others
to the point where they had to have a referendum on it, and they turned it down.
And the faculty and students were quite active outwardly on that issue too.
We don't want to get into it probably, but it led to interesting subsequent events regarding Joe McGraw's career as head of the department.
It ended up saving the taxpayers quite a bit of money.
Yeah.
I think the fact that it's been now 10 or 12 years and they got along fine without it shows something.
No, it was a bad thing.
Not terribly bad, but it just didn't make good sense.
So, what courses were you responsible for when you got here?
And you were here in 1965?
Six.
I think Joe started the program in 65, and I came the next year.
And you were number two on the faculty.
Well, I like to say I was number one, but he was administrator and faculty.
And then after you, it was Chewy.
I don't know whether it was Chewy or you.
I lost track.
I think Chewie was here in the summer of 1969, and I arrived in October.
And then he left right away for South America, Central and Latin America.
Yeah, Chile.
Yeah.
Well, to answer your question, which was what?
What did classes that I- Yeah, what part of the curriculum did you handle?
I think I, at that time, we stressed what we call labs more, the six unit practical courses in applied planning, if you will.
And one of the earliest was, interestingly enough, a plan for Texas City.
We called it a preliminary plan, and it was.
It stimulated, I think, planning, well, more intensive planning down there.
And it just happens that they came back a couple of years ago.
Julie and I were involved with Texas City again on sort of another plan, an update.
But interestingly out of that, it might be interesting that

This triggered quite a concern, it seems, by our colleagues in the, at that time, the American Institute of Planners, AIP, in that the college here using student labor was doing planning that should be done by consultants.
We had made it very clear that these were not professional, quote unquote,
plans, both to the client and to anybody that wanted to ask about it.
And it went so far as that they had a big brouhaha, and I wrote an answer to it which was pretty favorably received.
I can't find it nowadays, but in which I quoted the fact that the profession in there
Constitution or whatever it is at that time, said that one of their responsibilities was to work with students, give to students.
And it all worked out pretty well.
And my main point was that... And they had an educational responsibility as a chapter.
Right.
As they do now, as you well know, having them involved.
But as it turned out, I think we
What we said was that this will probably stimulate more work for consultants.
It turned out Texas City did hire a consultant later, as well as a lot of other cities.
But what I want to point out is that we early on took the so-called hands-on approach of so-called real-life situation and used that.
in the lab.
I taught those.
I also sort of specialized in the plan implementation.
I was one of the West Coast, being one of the West Coast group, was a disciple of the comprehensive physical plan, more or less, without getting into the implications of the other aspects of it.
and tried to embody that in both the lab and implementing the plan.
I might add that Joe McGraw took the first plunge and became a councilman.
I think I mentioned that earlier.
And I was appointed fairly early on to the Planning and Zoning Commission and put in four years there and then I decided to
get some experiences being one of the decision makers and ran for city council and served two terms.
And what I'm reciting that for is to sort of reinforce the fact that my one of my keen interests is in the political aspects of planning and the implementation of it.
How do you make the plan work?
In the accreditation team visit, it was pointed out that our curriculum was somewhat short on the political and implementation aspects of planning education.
And it seems to me that that was one of your contributions, that you seemed to be able to bring to the department an interest in public policy that other faculty members didn't.
I mean, that seemed to be your particular interest.
Well, I appreciate your keen awareness of that.
Well, I took it at a pretty basic level.
I wouldn't lay claim to being any kind of a policymaker, except as the plan makes policy.
And that we want the politicians to lay out, either through the plan or their own platform, their own agenda, whatever, some sort of
guidelines for the future and stick to them and make them accountable.
To me, that's the politics of planning.
You get things done.
Well, then you served two terms on the council and then you went off the council.
Yeah, we flip-flopped around, we the city, I'm speaking of, between having a total at-large
election to award system, or a combination of both.
I wasn't too happy with that.
And so I just bowed out for about nine years.
But during that nine years, I ran three times unsuccessfully.
I shouldn't mention that to posterity, but that's the case.
And then last April, April 87, I ran again and made it.
help some of my friends.
And a new mayor.
Right.
So now you're on the council again, doing good works for College Station.
Well, we haven't done much.
Of course, it's only been three months or so, but there haven't been any major issues as there were during that interim, like the location of a plant.
without too much planning thought into an establishment of a supposedly high-tech industrial park, which is yet to see any industry at all.
That being one of my favorite issues that I ran on.
Of course I lost on it three times, but I finally
I'm not sure that it was for that reason, but maybe it was.
It suffered from a lack of any kind of planning, really.
Looking at the department now that you are on a, what shall I say, a leisure schedule here, teaching about one class a year, is it?
That's right.
And you're essentially looking, your point of view is different.
How would you characterize any changes that have occurred in the department in terms of planning education and its administration and its offering and so forth?
Without getting too specific, I think it's a reflection of
the people who are the head of the department.
I think some of the things that went on early on were pretty much a reflection of the leaders and the faculty, and particularly the students.
Do you realize that at one time you and I were the only persons on the faculty who had not served as department head?
Yeah.
And so there have been changes, as you know, in the last 20 years, and I'm speaking of that time span being my tenure, more or less.
So not only did
The times change and the students change, but the leadership of the program changed.
And it's to be expected that there'd be a reflection or a re-emphasis or an emphasis on not only our administration in the department, but other administrative levels of the university.
principally the college, and of course we've gone through a lot of changes in the deanship, too.
Well, that leads to certain instability and concern for what the future is going to be of not only our department, but the college.
You know, we started as a part of
of the engineering college, which was a good stable.
That was the place to be at that time if you wanted the money and the stability and the power.
Of course, some of that has shifted now to other colleges.
Once we got our own college, things changed too.
A major thing, of course, and again, as I think I mentioned earlier on in this discussion, the students are a reflection of our national condition.
And we have to expect change.
As I said when I talked to you earlier, I'm not as close to the students because I only teach the one class once a year.
And then, of course, now we have expanded from the MUP degree into a PhD and an MSLD.
And a lot of students that I see out here today are not MUP students.
They're MSLD students.
And they're different.
They have different expectations and different professional goals.
And they're different kinds of folks than the MUP students are.

and that's again to be expected they come from different backgrounds and they certainly are looking for quite different things out of their practice when they leave here there aren't many of us on on the faculties of the different
departments in the university that are not a PhD, PhD level as you know.
And not many realized that at the time we, you and I, and a few others came into it, there was no PhD program anywhere.
And I think Don Foley, I don't think he got it in planning from UC, I think it was sociology or something.
So
That's right.
He was the first person I called doctor, academically.
But now the emphasis is on research, a lot of it, which goes along with the PhD program and requirement for being a member of the faculty.
Research and publication.
And we could spend another hour on that.
Well, it has changed.
The person without a Ph.D. has almost no chance of being admitted to higher education today.
It's simply not possible to join a faculty without it.
Whereas I think you're quite right.
When we were in the process of moving from practice into education, there was no way of getting a PhD in planning.
And in fact, if you look at this faculty today, there isn't one person on this faculty that has a PhD in planning.
They're in something else.
Economics in the case of Stover, or jurisprudence in the case of Pugh, or a foreign doctorate from Germany in the case of Wolfgang.
And I guess that Sherry Boehm has a PhD centered around health care from the University of Michigan.
